Macedonia’s referendum on the name change
The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum if the name of the country is to be changed to the 'Republic of Northern Macedonia', which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has prevented its attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia and claims that the name of its northern neighbour is a requirement on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments concluded an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change of name would undermine the identity of the Slavic majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said that he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubt if the minimum participation of 50% required for the referendum to be deemed valid will be reached.
The question on the ballot box in the referendum is this: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
However, the supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claim that it is worth renaming if it makes it possible for Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia was split, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the outcome for it to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a majority of two thirds of Parliament.
According to the State Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of registered voters voted.
"I am voting for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital of Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son, Dushko, will vote in the referendum in Macedonia on the change of name of the country, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia 30 September 2018.
Outside the Skopje Parliament, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, arranged a small stage and put out chairs in front of the tents set up by those who boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and Europe, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneak through the back door," said Kavardarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership in NATO would lead to much-needed investment in Macedonia, with unemployment of more than 20 per cent.
"I believe that the absolute majority will vote in favour, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev when he voted.
He said that a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonia Policy Survey Institute, between 30 and 43% of voters voted in the referendum, which falls under the minimum required participation.
According to another study conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 percent of the participants were expected to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them were going to vote yes.
For the referendum to count, 50 per cent of registered voters plus one vote are required.
If the referendum fails, it will be the first serious setback for the Western-centric government's policy since it took over last May.
