The newest frigate of the German fleet would have been launched in 2014 to replace warships from the time of the Cold War, but it will not be launched until at least next year due to incorrect systems and high costs, reported local media.
The launch of "Rheinland-Pfalz", the lead ship for the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigates, has now been postponed up to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit magazine, which quotes a military spokesman.
The vessel should have joined the fleet in 2014, but the problems that arose after delivery were fatal for the ambitious project.
The four ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class that the fleet ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen frigates.
They will include a powerful cannon, a range of aerial and target missiles, as well as certain sneak techniques, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to station the latest frigates for up to two years without contact with home ports.
But continuous delays mean that the groundbreaking warships - which allow Germany to project power abroad - are already out of date when they are put into operation, writes Die Zeit.
The fateful F125 frigate created headlines last year, when the German fleet officially refused to put the ship into operation and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time that the fleet returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the causes of the return, but German media indicated a number of important "soft and hardware errors" that made the warship useless if it was used on a combat mission.
Deficiencies in the software were particularly important as ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half of the crew of older frigates in the Bremen class.
It was also found that the ship has a significant excess weight, which leads to a deterioration in performance and limits its ability to perform future upgrades.
The 7 000 tonnes of heavy "Rheinland-Pfalz" are believed to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during the Second World War.
Apart from incorrect hardware, the entire project's price tag - including crew training - will also become a problem.
