National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
We hope that the results will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help steer future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the south and dwarf pistrils as well as brown loans and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in important places around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area view of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS conservation adviser, hopes that the results will reveal which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the boning and loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose risks, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks from Huskats.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in catching the prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organisation has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, examine bon and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Owner David Thompson says that the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here at Threeave we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of wheat trees and a lot of beneficial habitats.
But there is much about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before performing maintenance in real estate, since it is possible that accidental destruction of a single dwelling could kill up to 400 females and young people, and possibly annihilate an entire population.
The bats are peaceful and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or destroy their nest.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish Bat Conservation Trust Officer, has encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and too many of our species we don't know how their populations feel."
